{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492662"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:39:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:39:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1122"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1122"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.49,0.01,0.01,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1122"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104082"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1122"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1122"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86401"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"265"},{"type":"tags","id":"1149"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3556"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31241"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37281"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39707"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104082"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 45-year-old man presents with a left sided scrotal swelling which has been present for three years. Whilst it is hardly noticeable when he gets up in the morning, the swelling sometimes causes a heavy sensation towards the end of the day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination the left testis appears normal and there is a soft compressible swelling immediately above the testis, extending up towards the groin and is only visible and palpable when the patient stands up. There is no cough impulse at the groin. The rest of the physical examination of the external genitalia, groins and abdomen is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance","Ultrasound of the scrotum","Testicular tumour markers","Fine needle aspiration for cytology","CT abdomen and pelvis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is almost certainly an innocent varicocele. Varicocele formation can be found in about 20% of the male population and perhaps 40% of the sub fertile population. If the history of the swelling was measured in weeks rather than years, there might be some sinister underlying problem - such as a renal cell carcinoma - and some investigations might be appropriate. However, this swelling has been present for three years, does not appear to have changed in that time, disappears when the patient lies flat and does not cause the patient much trouble - \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassurance\u003C/strong\u003E should be all that is necessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ultrasound examination might be appropriate if the physical examination had not been able to define the problem. Whilst testicular cancers are a relatively common male malignancy, they are usually found in adolescents or young men. Apart from the age of the patient, the length of the history virtually excludes a neoplastic process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options provided might be appropriate if it was thought that the swelling was a testicular tumour. Apart from the physical characteristics of the swelling, the length of time it has been present would make a malignant cause very unlikely. Most patients with varicoceles do not require any form of intervention and treatment would only be indicated if the degree of varicosity was such that it was causing discomfort, inconvenience or perhaps a factor to be considered in managing a couple with fertility issues.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most varicoceles are innocent and do not require any investigation or treatment."],"references":["Wampler SM, Llanes M. Common Scrotal and Testicular Problems. Prim Care Clin Office Pract 2010; 37:613\u201326."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86401"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1122"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86401"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-29T12:27:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-29T12:28:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1122"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104082"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"dat